getDefinitionState

public java.lang.String getDefinitionState(LocaleContext locale)
Retrives the definition state string that indicates if this object is deprecated. The two possible values are: DEFINITION_STATE_ACTIVE DEFINITION_STATE_DEPRECATED

isDeprecated

public boolean isDeprecated(LocaleContext locale)
Returns a boolean value which indicates if this definition object is deprecated. In the personalization case, this method indicates if the definition object is deprecated after applying personalization. If the base definition object is deprecated, then this method returns true regardless the pers def. That said, pers def could only change an active def object to be deprecated, but could not do the opposite way. If the base def object is not deprecated, then the method will look corresponding pers def object to decide if it is deprecated. For internal framework use only.

For internal use only. Application developers should not use this

addPropertySetName

protected void addPropertySetName(int index,
                                  java.lang.String propertySetName)
Add the given property set name to the list of property sets in this object at the given index. If the property set exists in the list, then this method will move the existing entry to the given index. If the propertySetName is null, then this method simply returns.
